{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01TaMypLGcj9kK2aAJ7M8gLG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `Sql` interface has call signatures (overloaded). When `TransactionSql` uses `Omit<Sql<TTypes>, ...>`, the call signatures are lost because `Omit` creates a mapped type that strips callable signatures.\n\nThis is a known TypeScript limitation — `Omit` doesn't preserve call signatures.\n\nSo the issue is that `tx` inside `sql.begin((tx) => ...)` has type `TransactionSql<{}>`, and while at runtime it IS callable and has `.unsafe()`, TypeScript's `Omit` type helper loses the call signature.\n\nBut wait, `.unsafe()` should still work because it's a named property, not a call signature. \n\nLet me look more carefully at the actual error location. The error points to line 68, column 11, which seems to be in the middle of a statement. I need to trace through the file to see what's actually on that line and whether the error is about calling `tx` directly or something else with the `.unsafe()` method. Writing migration setup code... I'm seeing the issue now — the error says `.unsafe()` isn't callable on `TransactionSql`, but it should be inherited from `Sql` since it's a named property that wouldn't be stripped by the `Omit`. Let me think through whether the type definition is actually preserving that method correctly or if there's something about how `TransactionSql` is constructed that's removing it.\n\nActually, I should just try a simpler approach — instead of relying on the transaction callback pattern, I can execute the migration content and the insert statement separately, both wrapped in explicit `BEGIN` and `COMMIT` calls, since the migration SQL is already idempotent with its `IF NOT EXISTS` clauses. I need to dig into the TypeScript type definitions for the postgres library. The `TransactionSql` type uses `Omit` which should preserve named properties like `.unsafe()` but loses call signatures, so the error on the tagged template call must be coming from somewhere else. Let me trace through the actual line numbers in the file to figure out what's really happening.\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. The simpler solution is to just avoid using the tagged template syntax inside the transaction callback altogether and use `.unsafe()` for both queries instead.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":540,"cache_read_input_tokens":54337,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":540},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"43f990b3-3b80-4952-b266-f65de083e062","uuid":"b92fdd6a-f249-42ef-804e-f1de39545cba"}
